                                    Finance

                            Mark Buthman: Facilitating and framing issues







            June 19, 2013 | Written by: THINK Leaders 

    Categorized: Finance | Pacesetters 


Share this post:   


Mark Buthman,Chief financial officer, Kimberly-Clark Corporation
Kimberly-Clark has a great tradition of innovation. It pioneered five of the eight consumer product categories where it does business, including facial tissues, training and youth pants, and bathroom tissue. Now the company is under pressure to innovate in the way it does business, too, as it drives an ambitious international expansion. Mark Buthman, who has been chief financial officer for more than 10 years, sees the CFO as a facilitator and framer of issues, someone who can help the company expand rapidly even while improving its profitability. Here, he explains how the role of CFO at Kimberly-Clark is changing.
What are the primary opportunities and challenges that face Kimberly-Clark?
The biggest driver of our business is international growth. As per capita incomes grow around the world, our categories are among the first that consumers enter for the first time, or where they aspire to better performance, better brands.
At the same time, as the economy has become more difficult in developed markets, we need to provide differentiation and clear value in terms of the performance and the perception of our products. People are nervous about spending. Our products have to be demonstrably better than the alternatives.
So we have to have great product innovation and great product performance and we have to communicate that performance effectively, all over the world.
In the emerging markets, are you designing new business models and changing pricing to grow rapidly?
The key for us is balancing the global approach—scalable ideas and model—with the local market and local consumer. Keeping that balance is a challenge because you want to drive scale, but in local markets there are different demand dynamics that you have to respond to.
For instance, in China, with disposable diapers, there are clear expectations in terms of fit and leakage protection, and yet they don’t want to change their babies as often as folks in the United States do. With Huggies, we have to figure out how to deliver to those expectations at a price point the parents in China can afford. We’ve had to find a way to manufacture and to provide the same functional benefit at a lower cost.
How did the CFO function play a role in that?
We partnered with the businesses to design a new product development, procurement, manufacturing and marketing model in China. First we framed the problem that needed to be solved. Then we used information and analytics to provide some options.
What about in the developed markets. What role are you playing there?
In every one of our categories, we have to be competitive on price and have the best- performing product. That’s a universal truth. In a big box store, where you have our products side by side with another premium product, we have to price very competitively or the consumer may switch. So the role we play is in working with all the parts of our company—supply chain, product development, manufacturing— to create a cost structure that will support sustainable investment and make the product successful. We bring the various stakeholders together. We’re at the table when every key strategic decision is made. We bring an independent, economic perspective to the decision.
You have been CFO for more than 10 years. How is the role changing?
Some things are the same. We don’t have unlimited resources, so the CFO has to be the champion of resource allocation. Next, we help with setting goals and targets that balance investments. We take into consideration the degree of difficulty in getting something done, risks, and prospects for growth, profitability and returns on capital. Then we hold teams accountable for their business results.
What’s changing, though, is the role of information technology in business. Earlier, the CFO had access to all the information, aggregated it and used it when making decisions. Now, thanks to the Internet and other technologies, people throughout the organization have great access to information. In the old days my job was directing and deciding. Now I should be facilitating, orchestrating and influencing rather than mandating. My expectation for my team and myself is that we develop a compelling business case and champion the change. This way, we’re working to drive change that is embraced. We’re not so much pushing as the organization is pulling.
How do you help drive agility within the business?
The competitive environment has accelerated so much that we’ve got to be much more nimble, much more agile, much more wired in. In the planning process, there are much shorter lead times to project what the business is going to do.
At Kimberly-Clark, we talk a lot about taking smart risks. In a lot of companies, the finance role is being a policeman. But, here, we’re more of a teacher, a leader, a facilitator. If our role is just to say no any time there’s a risk on the table, we’ re not going to create much value for our shareholders. Our job is to help frame issues and get the organization to take smart, calculated risks.
Will you provide an example where you played the facilitator and framer role in an effort that let to a new revenue opportunity?
One area where we have done that is in the international expansion. We have helped the company size up the emerging markets opportunities and figure out how to successfully compete in them. Now, about half of our total capital spend is on building capacity and innovation. In 2012, for the first time, we spent more capital in developing markets than in developed markets. The shift in our capital allocation didn’t mirror the growth of business in these newer markets; it led the transformation of the business. That was a shift that my team led.
At the same time, we have dramatically increased marketing in developing markets—to establish our brands there. We have done that while increasing our gross margins. That’s possible because of the cost improvements we’re making.
What is technology’s role in making the company more efficient, innovative and competitive?
The Internet and transparency of consumer information and competitive cost information is changing the way the whole world works. Your ability to sustain a pricing advantage in an Internet-driven world is about a nanosecond. So we’re joined at the hip with the CIO, Jennifer Sepull; in fact, she reports to me. Our goal is to provide information so business leaders can make better, faster and higher quality decisions.
My vision for our organization is to have the right information on the desktop for all of our decision makers, so they can make a quality decision when they need to make it. We’re not there yet. The CIO and the CFO can partner to bring that reality to life.
We need mobile and collaboration technologies to drive team engagement across functional and geographic boundaries. If I can use technology to get information more rapidly across our organization, it gives us the opportunity to unlock the best ideas.
Technology also improves our ability to do things better. We can compare our performance against benchmarks. And we can share our problem-solving experiences. I don’t have to wrestle with an issue by myself. I can find somebody else who has dealt with the same issue already, and learn from him or her. The connections that technology provides are invaluable.
How has your relationship with the IT function changed over the years?
In the old days, the CFO was the gatekeeper of the money. The CIO had to come and ask for money, like everybody else. Now, it’s more a conversation about how we invest in IT as a core capability. We’re helping control costs by adopting standard technologies and standard ways of handling data across the organization, and by eliminating redundant systems. Once you’ve done that you can free up resources to spend on new capabilities, on innovation. So, the most important role for the CFO is framing issues that create new opportunities, enthusiasm and energy throughout the company.

