Coaching the Next Generation: Mark Buthman, Board Director and Retired CFO







 







Mark Buthman






 
Mark Buthman spent 33 years at Kimberly-Clark, working his way up from a cost analyst to CFO and serving in several non-finance posts along the way. Having retired at the end of 2015, he now sits on the boards of for-profit and non-profit organizations and serves on the Financial Executives Advisory Group for Deloitte’s CFO Program.
Mr. Buthman discusses what his 12-year term as CFO taught him, the steps he took to develop finance employees to their full potential, and how he helps to guide current and aspiring CFOs in this conversation with Sanford (Sandy) Cockrell III, U.S. national managing partner, CFO Program, Deloitte LLP. Mr. Buthman also talks about the relationship between the board and the CFO and what boards expect of CFOs.
 







Sanford Cockrell III






 
Sandy Cockrell: You spent your entire career at Kimberly-Clark, but not always in finance. What were the key milestones in reaching the CFO position?
Mark Buthman: I always wanted to drive business results, to lead teams, and to coach, influence and develop people. Those were more important motivators for me than becoming CFO. In fact, I think the non-finance roles I took on were the most important because they forced me to lead without relying on my financial skills and experiences. Running a tissue plant, for example, was a fantastic leadership opportunity because I literally brought nothing to the table other than perhaps the ability to do the budget. Everything else was about getting the team to where it needed to go.
At one point, I was also asked to support some M&A transactions, but I didn’t have extensive training in it at the time. Those projects came with a lot of responsibility and forced me to learn skills and a new nomenclature very rapidly. They really tested my learning agility, and I’m grateful that I had the opportunity to stretch myself in a new space.
Sandy Cockrell: You believe in the value of measuring and improving employee engagement. How have you seen such efforts translate into results?
Mark Buthman: I think a highly engaged workforce correlates to improved bottom-line performance. About halfway into my tenure as CFO we did an engagement survey that showed that some people in my finance organization didn’t feel like they were empowered to take risks. They felt like they were more encouraged to cut costs and avoid risks than to drive growth in the business. That frustrated me because business is about taking calculated risks, and to me the finance organization is the ideal resource to be able to help the business determine risk/reward tradeoffs.
I shared my concern with the head of risk management at the time, and he worked with someone from our legal team to put together a program called “Smart Risk-Taking.” Within about 18 months the program trained 5,000 people, both within and outside finance. “Smart Risk-Taking” ultimately became an element of one of the core behaviors we expected from anyone in a leadership role.
Sandy Cockrell: You also have advocated for pushing decision-making down in the organization. What is the benefit of doing that?
Mark Buthman: The role of a finance leader is to drive business performance, and much of that depends on empowering the organization to make smart decisions strategically, tactically and operationally. There are times when you have to take the decision or draw a bright line that can’t be crossed, but I think leaders are most effective when they take on the roles of coach, teacher and influencer so their teams make the calls and own the results.
Prior to the digital revolution, the role of the CFO was to accumulate information from different silos, bring it together and make decisions at the top of the organization. There was really no other way to do it. Today most of the information needed to make decisions—even big, strategic decisions—is readily available to many people in the organization, which gives the CFO a golden opportunity to push decision-making down and empower teams. To do that, one has to be good at articulating a clear vision and giving people a framework. One colleague described it as “the freedom of boundaries,” meaning that he understood his latitude to make decisions as long as he knew what lines couldn’t be crossed. As the CFO, when you empower teams this way, it can free you up to have much greater influence on the business.  If every decision needs to come to your desk, that’s going to slow decision making and limit your impact.
Sandy Cockrell: You have significant experience as a board director. What has it taught you about the relationship between the board and the CFO?
Mark Buthman: Serving on boards has exposed me to a diverse range of business strategies and leadership styles, and has given me an appreciation for the importance of looking at a business from the outside in. As a CFO, my experience as a board member helped me understand how to communicate to the board the essential things they need to know while keeping the discussions at a high level. Until I sat on the other side of those conversations as a director, I didn’t fully realize the importance of communications from a board member’s perspective.
I stress to sitting CFOs that working with the audit committee, in particular, can provide them with an opportunity to highlight talent in the finance organization. That helps foster more trust within the audit committee that the right people are in the right roles and they are going to do the right thing. Board members can actually help CFOs develop their talent because they bring an objective perspective free of the day-to-day relationships with people.
I’ve also learned that what boards want to see most in a CFO is someone with a strong functional and ethical foundation, a strategic mindset, and the ability to attract and build exceptional talent with strong communication and influencing skills. And, of course, CFOs need to understand when and how to alert the board to an emerging issue. Having served in both roles, I encourage CFOs to view the board as a resource and to make the effort to reach out to an individual board member if their skills can help address a particular issue, including talent matters.
Sandy Cockrell: You spend some of your time coaching other CFOs. What do you encourage them to focus on?
Mark Buthman: I tell new CFOs that they now have broader responsibilities than they’ve ever had before, yet they have only half the time to meet them all. That’s because more of their time is committed to board meetings, investor calls and roadshows, earnings, forecast reviews, CEO leadership meetings, travel and other activities. Their calendar may be booked a full year out or more. So as CFO, the ability to manage your time effectively and to invest it where it makes the most difference is something you have to get your arms around. One technique that helped me—even although it goes against conventional teaching—was to drop most of my one-on-one meetings. We made exceptions for cases where someone needed coaching, help in setting direction or problem-solving, or needed to communicate an emerging issue.
I also encourage the CFOs I work with to help their teams identify and act on their purpose and values as much or more than the work they do.  For example, when I became CFO I had a game plan to improve our core finance capabilities, set a clear tone at the top, have a robust set of internal controls and address talent development, typical expectations for many finance organizations. I refer to those as the “what.”
Despite all the work being done, however, I had the sense that our finance organization, including myself, was still not reaching its full potential. Eventually, I realized it was because we had not addressed the “why.”  So together we rallied around a very simple message: to empower our leaders to think like a CFO with a mission to drive business results, inspire our teams and each other, and transform the way we did our work.  If everyone in an organization feels empowered to focus on those three things, good outcomes can happen.  At the end of the day if an organization is 80% right and 100% aligned that is a terrific result, and much better than being 100% right and only 20% aligned.
Editor’s note: This article is part of an ongoing series of interviews with CEOs, CFOs and other executives. Mr. Buthman’s participation in this article is solely for educational purposes based on his knowledge of the subject, and the views expressed by him are solely his own. This article should not be deemed or construed to be for soliciting business for any of the organizations Mr. Buthman has represented in his career nor does Deloitte advocate or endorse their services or products.





